entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Handle restarts in StyleSheetHandler
entry.content:
Since declarations that fail to parse are now retried as nested style

rules, we can end up with CSSParserObserver events that claim that we

both have a failed declaration and a valid style rule at the same

offset. This is technically correct, but StyleSheetHandler needs a

better interpretation of this to stay in a consistent state.



In short, we now remove the CSSPropertySourceData produced by

the conflicting ObserveProperty event if a valid style rule is

seen in the same offset. This means that:



- Token sequences that fail as declarations, but pass as

style rules will appear as style rules.

- Token sequences that fail as declarations, and that also fail

as style rules will will appear as declarations (like before).



For token sequences that pass as declarations, there is of course

no difference, because we never retry parsing as style rules for

those sequences.



Bug: 1427259

entry.title: [bookmarks] Carry over local UUIDs when uploading all local bookmarks
entry.content:
When the destination BookmarkModel doesn't contain a colliding UUID, it

is best to reuse the local bookmark's original UUID when copying it to

the account BookmarkModel instance.



This makes it less likely that, in the long run, users run into

undesired bookmark duplicates, as UUID-based matching is very robust.



As a minor side change, the hashing function used for semantic-based

matching is improved, hoping that it improves the performance for

worst-case scenarios where many sibling nodes shared the same title.

entry.title: [Tab Switcher] Mark tab as hidden after showing
entry.content:
Call Tab#hide() for the current tab when finished showing the Tab

Switcher, including animations and thumbnail capture. This marks the

Tab and its WebContents as hidden and should reduce extra work such as

animations. Because the tab is selected it will still have a foreground

renderer binding which should prevent any negative side-effect.

Clicking the selected tab or pressing back invokes setIndex which will

undo the side-effect of the hide [1].



This action will be cancelled if exiting the tab switcher before the

thumbnail is captured.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/android/features/tab_ui/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/tasks/tab_management/TabListMediator.java;drc=f70d55e43da21fb79c04798c865de121f94d188a;l=371

entry.title: Condition language-dependent parsing on AutofillPageLanguageDetection.
entry.content:
FormStructure::current_page_language_ has two uses:

- To attach it to the upload request (for the metadata pipeline).

- To use language-dependent regexes when AutofillParsingPatternProvider

is enabled.

It is determined using some translate API.



Setting a form structure's language happens at multiple places, but most

notably right before parsing a form on page load. At this point, the

page language might or might not have been by translate yet. If it has

been determined, that page language is used for local heuristics when

pattern provider is enabled, even if AutofillPageLanguageDetection is

disabled.



At the moment, AutofillPageLanguageDetection only controls if an

additional local heuristics call happens after the page language was

determined (using a LanguageDetectionObserver in AutofillManager).



This CL changes the parsing logic slightly to condition the use of

current_page_language_ on AutofillPageLanguageDetection. This only has

an effect when AutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled but

AutofillPageLanguageDetection is disabled. This allows rolling out

pattern provider without page language detection (by not providing a

page language, regexes of all languages are used).



The metadata pipeline is unaffected by this change. This logic was

added long before pattern provider and AutofillPageLanguageDetection in

~2018 by http://crrev.com/c/1358634.

entry.title: ui-controls: Remove set_toplevel_bounds request
entry.content:
Many TabDragging tests pass require control over browser windows'

bounds, which isn't possible on Wayland without aura-shell. Thus, a

set_toplevel_bounds request was added to ui-controls to help with making

these tests pass on Linux ozone/wayland.



However, it turned out that implementing this request in Weston is quite

complicated. It's a lot easier to take a different approach: use

emulated mouse events to resizes and move the browser windows like a

real user would do. This is being implemented in

https://crrev.com/c/4738688, and it seems to work great.



Thus, we don't need the set_toplevel_bounds request after all, and can

remove it.

order, ignoring whitespace:



1. Consume an ident. (Normally a property name).

2. Consume a semicolon.

3. Consume the value tokens. This means scanning until the first

top-level semicolon. Actual value-parsing happens later.

4. Check if the ident from (1) is a valid property.

5. Parse the value.



The problem is that we're checking for property validity (4) *after*

consuming the value tokens (3). This is bad for nested contexts,

because (3) is potentially a lot of wasted tokenization work if

we're going to restart the stream due to a property being invalid (4).



Therefore, this CL refactors ConsumeDeclaration such that

ConsumeValue generally happens *after* we check for property

validity.



On my machine, with CSSNestingIdent set to status:stable,

the included performance test takes around 13ms with the optimization

and 495ms without the optimization. The important part here is that

there's a clear signal in the case of a regression.



The style perftest (style_perftest.cc) seems neutral for this CL.

entry.title: [AWC] Add `display-state` CSS @media feature
entry.content:
The new `display-state` CSS will enable using CSS or JS @media query to

know in which state the window is. Possible values are: `normal`,

`fullscreen`, `maximized` and `minimized`.



For example:



```css

@media (display-state: minimized) {

.button {

/*CSS to be applied*/

}

}

```



```js

window.matchMedia('(display-state: minimized)').matches

```



Demo: go/display-state-demo



I2P thread

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/oCxWg8q_OQY/m/LUTw0T5cCQAJ



Public explainer is available @

https://github.com/ivansandrk/additional-windowing-controls/blob/main/awc-explainer.md

entry.title: [BRP/clang-plugin] Adjust exclusions for raw_ptr bad cast detector

Exclude followings from `check-bad-raw-ptr-cast`.



- Casts in system header except "__bit/bit_cast.h"

- Casts in third_party except blink

- Implicit casts in comparison context

raw_ptr* raw_ptr;

void* void_ptr;

if (raw_ptr == void_ptr) {}

void f(void* p) {}

void f(int v) {}

template

void call_f(T t) { f(t); }

^ implicit cast may or may not happen here

It is hard to convert this into explicit cast.

entry.title: [Files]: Adds duration checks to recent source parameters.
entry.content:
Adds start and end times to parameters. If maximum duration is not set the end time is set to maximum possible time. Adds IsLate method to allow recent sources monitor if they still have time left to descend into subdirectories. In this CL there is no attempt made to terminate an already running directory scan.

use `getBoundingClientRect()`. `getBoundingClientRect()` gives values

relative to the viewport/window, while `offset*` values are relative

to the top of the document and therefore does not take into account

scroll position.
